{"post_stream":{"posts":[{"id":3146142,"name":"pinkguava06","username":"HarrisonFord","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/harrisonford/{size}/246558_2.png","created_at":"2023-02-15T19:30:08.743Z","cooked":"

Close to finishing my code to make the robot auto-balance with a NavX. I only have 2 errors, and the driveCartesian is the only one I don’t know how to fix properly.
The error reads as follows:
“The method driveCartesian(double, double, double, Rotation2d) in the type MecanumDrive is not applicable for the arguments (double, double, double, int)”
Is the new WPILib messing with this? It worked fine in the past.

try {
myRobot.driveCartesian(xAxisRate, yAxisRate, stick.getTwist(), 0);
} catch (RuntimeException ex) {
String err_string = "Drive system error: " + ex.getMessage();
DriverStation.reportError(err_string, true);
}

You’re passing an integer (0) as the last arg. It needs a Rotation2d object. You’ll need to do something like Rotation2d.fromDegrees(0) instead.

Even simpler
myRobot.driveCartesian(xAxisRate, yAxisRate, stick.getTwist());

Since the gyro parameter is only used for field oriented drive, and by setting it to 0 you aren’t using field oriented drive, you can use the other function signature.
